[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:sails-node/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:sails-node/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:sails-node/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:sails-node/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:sails-node/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:sails-node/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:sails-node/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:sails-node/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:sails-node/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:sails-node/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:sails-node/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:sails-node/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:sails-node/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:sails-node/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:sails-node/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:sails-node/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:sails-node/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:sails-node/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:sails-node/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:sails-node/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:sails-node/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:sails-node/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:sails-node/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:sails-node/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:sails-node/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:sails-node/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:sails-node/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:sails-node/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:sails-node/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:sails-node/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:sails-node/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:sails-node/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:sails-node/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:sails-node/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:sails-node/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:sails-node/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:sails-node/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:sails-node/sails-js] Sails.js is built on Node.js and Express.js, enabling applications to be written in JavaScript.
[src:sails-node/sails-js] This includes models, views, controllers, configuration files, and adapters (e.g., database).
[src:sails-node/sails-js] Similar to Ruby on Rails, Sails.js provides an object-relational mapping interface using Waterline.js, which abstracts the database interaction layer.
[src:sails-node/sails-js] A number of other packages are included to enable fast auto-generated REST APIs, WebSockets by default using Socket.io; and compatibility features making it front-end agnostic (AngularJS, React.js, Android, iOS, etc.).
[src:sails-node/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:sails-node/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:sails-node/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:sails-node/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:sails-node/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:sails-node/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:sails-node/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:sails-node/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:sails-node/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:sails-node/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:sails-node/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:sails-node/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:sails-node/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:sails-node/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:sails-node/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:sails-node/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:sails-node/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:sails-node/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:sails-node/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:sails-node/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:sails-node/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:sails-node/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:sails-node/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:sails-node/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:sails-node/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
